            <p>COMMERCIAL BUREAU OF THE AMERICAN REPUBLICS.<lb/>
                DEPARTMENT OF STATE.<lb/>
                WASHINGTON. U. S. A.<lb/></p>
            <p>November 1&#44; 1890.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                &#35;546 North Fifth Street&#44;<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44; Pennsylvania.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>I take the liberty of addressing you by permission of<lb/> our mutual friend&#44; Prof. Cyrus Adler&#44; who tells me that you<lb/> know a great many things that I ought to know&#44; and will be<lb/> willing to tell them.  Mr. Adler has&#44; perhaps&#44; told you some&#45;<lb/>thing of my plan for an exhibit at the Columbian Exposition&#44;<lb/> of which I enclose you a copy.  In arranging further details<lb/> of this plan&#44; I would like to know something about an Italian<lb/> Exposition that was held in London in 1889&#44; where were exhib&#45;<lb/>ited models of vessels similar to those in which Columbus<lb/> sailed.  Any information you can give me on this subject<lb/> will be gratefully appreciated.<lb/>  Very truly yours&#44;<lb/> William E. Curtis.<lb/></p>
            </body>
